version: 1
display_name: VCFI-9X-000109 - The VMware Cloud Foundation Operations PostgreSQL service must log all connection attempts.
global_description: |-
  For completeness of forensic analysis, it is necessary to track successful and failed attempts to log on to PostgreSQL. Setting "log_connections" to "on" will cause each attempted connection to the server to be logged, as well as successful completion of client authentication.
osfinger:
  - VMware Photon OS-5
refs:
  disa_stig:
    - VCFI-9X-000109
  srg:
    - SRG-APP-000503-DB-000350
  cci:
    - CCI-000172
  nist:
    - AU-12 c
benchmark_id:
  vcf9_operations_postgresql:
    type: custom
    desc: The VMware Cloud Foundation Operations PostgreSQL service must log all connection attempts.
    control_id: VCFI-9X-000109
    scored: true
    profile:
      - default
    information: |-
      As a database administrator, perform the following at the command prompt:

      # su - postgres -c "/opt/vmware/vpostgres/current/bin/psql -p 5433 -A -t -c 'SHOW log_connections;'"

      Example result:

      on

      If the "log_connections" setting is not configured to "on", this is a finding.
    rationale: |-
      For completeness of forensic analysis, it is necessary to track successful and failed attempts to log on to PostgreSQL. Setting "log_connections" to "on" will cause each attempted connection to the server to be logged, as well as successful completion of client authentication.
    remediation: |-
      As a database administrator, perform the following at the command prompt:

      # su - postgres -c "/opt/vmware/vpostgres/current/bin/psql -p 5433 -A -t -c \"ALTER SYSTEM SET log_connections TO 'on';\""

      Reload the PostgreSQL service by running the following command:

      # systemctl restart vpostgres-repl.service
